WEBVTT

NOTE
This file was generated by Descript <www.descript.com>

00:00:05.290 --> 00:00:08.010
Hello, hello, hello, and welcome

00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:09.809
to English Learning for Curious

00:00:09.809 --> 00:00:12.680
Minds, by Leonardo English, the show

00:00:12.690 --> 00:00:14.369
where you can listen to fascinating

00:00:14.370 --> 00:00:16.759
stories and learn weird and wonderful

00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:18.770
things about the world at the same

00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:20.589
time as improving your English.

00:00:21.039 --> 00:00:23.500
I'm Alastair Budge, and today

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:25.669
we are going to be talking about

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:27.610
the life of Charlie Chaplin.

00:00:28.210 --> 00:00:30.800
He is, by some measures, the most

00:00:30.810 --> 00:00:34.099
famous actor in history, and the story

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:37.389
of his life is as fascinating as it is

00:00:37.389 --> 00:00:40.609
controversial, and as unlikely as it

00:00:40.609 --> 00:00:43.430
was, in hindsight, almost inevitable.

00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:46.620
It’s a tale of poverty, wealth,

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:49.970
comedy, tragedy, sexual misconduct,

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:52.920
communism, fascism, and more.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:55.420
So, let's not waste a minute

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:57.280
and get right into it.

00:00:58.760 --> 00:00:59.930
You might know the English

00:00:59.930 --> 00:01:02.390
expression “rags to riches”.

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:05.870
We use it to describe the story of

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:08.550
someone who goes from growing up poor,

00:01:09.070 --> 00:01:11.730
without much money, to great success.

00:01:12.990 --> 00:01:16.059
It’s a term that journalists like to use.

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:18.720
The riches part is normally

00:01:18.770 --> 00:01:20.920
factually correct, as the people

00:01:20.920 --> 00:01:22.720
they are describing are usually

00:01:22.730 --> 00:01:25.250
rich and famous; they have “riches”.

00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:29.850
The rags part is not always quite correct.

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:32.770
Sure, it might be someone who grew

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:35.259
up without much money, but they were

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:37.449
normally not literally destitute,

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:40.080
forced to wear rags for clothes.

00:01:41.410 --> 00:01:43.940
The story of Charlie Chaplin, however,

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:47.100
can most certainly be described

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:50.329
as rags to riches, as he went from

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:52.690
extreme poverty to becoming the

00:01:52.719 --> 00:01:55.810
best-paid actor, debatably even the

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:59.240
highest-paid person, in the entire world.

00:02:00.510 --> 00:02:03.434
He was born on April 16th,

00:02:03.632 --> 00:02:06.969
1889, in Victorian London, the

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:09.470
second son of two entertainers.

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:12.727
His mother was a singer, his father

00:02:12.727 --> 00:02:15.807
also worked on stage, but they separated

00:02:15.877 --> 00:02:17.967
shortly after Charlie was born.

00:02:19.137 --> 00:02:21.687
Life was tough from the start.

00:02:22.877 --> 00:02:25.637
His father was an alcoholic, largely

00:02:25.687 --> 00:02:28.187
absent from the young boy’s life, and

00:02:28.197 --> 00:02:30.587
provided little financial support.

00:02:31.677 --> 00:02:34.127
His mother tried to make ends meet,

00:02:34.487 --> 00:02:36.807
singing in music halls, which were the

00:02:36.817 --> 00:02:38.417
popular entertainment venues of the

00:02:38.417 --> 00:02:41.037
time that combined comedy, singing,

00:02:41.227 --> 00:02:43.247
and short theatrical performances.

00:02:44.247 --> 00:02:47.337
She was good, reportedly, but it

00:02:47.337 --> 00:02:49.617
was a tough, competitive world,

00:02:49.817 --> 00:02:52.107
and money was hard to come by.

00:02:53.057 --> 00:02:55.627
Still, it was the only world the young

00:02:55.627 --> 00:02:58.847
boy knew, and his early years were spent

00:02:58.867 --> 00:03:01.627
watching his mother sing and perform on

00:03:01.627 --> 00:03:04.987
stage, copying her, as any child might do.

00:03:06.547 --> 00:03:08.617
And when he was just five years

00:03:08.617 --> 00:03:11.467
old, he took to the stage himself.

00:03:12.737 --> 00:03:14.657
It wasn’t planned, I should add.

00:03:15.087 --> 00:03:17.617
His mother was on stage, mid-performance,

00:03:17.907 --> 00:03:20.047
singing to a packed audience.

00:03:21.167 --> 00:03:24.187
And then, her voice started to crack.

00:03:24.997 --> 00:03:25.797
She couldn't sing.

00:03:26.457 --> 00:03:28.347
Her voice simply failed.

00:03:29.477 --> 00:03:31.967
The audience started to boo, to

00:03:31.977 --> 00:03:33.789
jeer at her, making fun of her.

00:03:35.257 --> 00:03:37.317
The young Charlie was watching from

00:03:37.317 --> 00:03:39.207
the wings, the side of the stage.

00:03:39.817 --> 00:03:42.117
The theatre manager, desperate to

00:03:42.127 --> 00:03:44.807
salvage the situation, pushed the young

00:03:44.807 --> 00:03:47.577
boy onto the stage to sing instead.

00:03:48.737 --> 00:03:49.247
He did.

00:03:49.587 --> 00:03:51.097
And the crowd loved him.

00:03:52.037 --> 00:03:54.467
The thing was, his mother’s breakdown

00:03:54.467 --> 00:03:57.487
on stage wasn’t simple exhaustion

00:03:57.617 --> 00:04:00.197
or some temporary illness; it was

00:04:00.197 --> 00:04:02.557
caused by what we would now politely

00:04:02.557 --> 00:04:04.877
describe as mental health issues.

00:04:05.737 --> 00:04:08.047
Her mental health was deteriorating,

00:04:08.387 --> 00:04:10.207
and she wasn’t able to

00:04:10.207 --> 00:04:11.967
financially support her children.

00:04:13.167 --> 00:04:15.967
So, she did what many destitute

00:04:16.027 --> 00:04:18.407
Victorian parents were forced to do:

00:04:19.027 --> 00:04:21.467
send their children to the workhouse,

00:04:22.037 --> 00:04:24.227
and that is where, at the age of

00:04:24.227 --> 00:04:26.897
seven, Charlie Chaplin ended up,

00:04:27.257 --> 00:04:28.917
together with his older brother.

00:04:30.337 --> 00:04:33.677
Now, it’s worth pausing here for a moment

00:04:33.857 --> 00:04:36.677
to talk about the idea of a “workhouse”.

00:04:37.857 --> 00:04:40.527
Workhouses, in the Victorian era,

00:04:40.897 --> 00:04:43.167
were places where the very poorest

00:04:43.177 --> 00:04:45.697
people in society were sent if they

00:04:45.697 --> 00:04:48.077
could not support themselves, or if

00:04:48.077 --> 00:04:49.677
their parents could not support them.

00:04:50.927 --> 00:04:54.697
And life inside was deliberately harsh.

00:04:55.317 --> 00:04:57.487
Families were often separated,

00:04:57.737 --> 00:05:00.487
food was basic, and the work

00:05:00.637 --> 00:05:02.787
was hard and monotonous.

00:05:03.777 --> 00:05:06.697
The idea was not just to provide shelter,

00:05:07.077 --> 00:05:09.377
but to discourage people from ever

00:05:09.377 --> 00:05:11.917
needing to rely on public help again.

00:05:12.877 --> 00:05:15.067
If you know the story of Oliver Twist,

00:05:15.347 --> 00:05:18.277
or you have ever seen the classic 1968

00:05:18.327 --> 00:05:20.887
musical adaptation, you might remember

00:05:20.947 --> 00:05:23.337
the scenes from the workhouse: children

00:05:23.337 --> 00:05:26.247
in rags, forced to work all day long,

00:05:26.527 --> 00:05:28.847
and given barely anything to eat.

00:05:30.097 --> 00:05:32.507
And the reality the young Charlie

00:05:32.517 --> 00:05:34.677
Chaplin lived was the reality

00:05:34.907 --> 00:05:36.477
Charles Dickens described.

00:05:37.177 --> 00:05:39.997
For a young child, it was a brutal

00:05:39.997 --> 00:05:42.587
environment, and Chaplin would

00:05:42.587 --> 00:05:44.757
later describe how humiliating

00:05:44.987 --> 00:05:46.977
and frightening this time was.

00:05:48.137 --> 00:05:50.567
He and his brother did get out, and

00:05:50.857 --> 00:05:52.397
they briefly went to live with their

00:05:52.397 --> 00:05:55.527
father, who was a full-on, abusive

00:05:55.527 --> 00:05:57.387
and violent alcoholic by this point.

00:05:58.527 --> 00:06:01.097
The authorities got involved, the boys

00:06:01.097 --> 00:06:03.377
were reunited with their mother, but

00:06:03.823 --> 00:06:06.337
her mental health had continued to

00:06:06.337 --> 00:06:09.307
deteriorate, and she was completely

00:06:09.397 --> 00:06:11.347
incapable of looking after them.

00:06:12.467 --> 00:06:14.577
The boys – Charlie and his brother

00:06:14.907 --> 00:06:17.147
– would spend several years floating

00:06:17.157 --> 00:06:18.822
from workhouse to workhouse.

00:06:19.787 --> 00:06:22.537
From an early age, Chaplin learned

00:06:22.587 --> 00:06:25.757
two important lessons: how easily a

00:06:25.757 --> 00:06:27.827
person could fall through the cracks

00:06:27.827 --> 00:06:30.337
of society, and how quickly the

00:06:30.337 --> 00:06:32.137
world could turn its back on you.

00:06:33.121 --> 00:06:35.497
But he would also learn something

00:06:35.497 --> 00:06:39.037
else; performance could be a way out.

00:06:40.247 --> 00:06:42.777
He discovered that he had a remarkable

00:06:42.797 --> 00:06:45.007
ability to make people laugh,

00:06:45.417 --> 00:06:47.687
not through jokes, but through

00:06:47.697 --> 00:06:50.617
movement, timing, and expression.

00:06:51.902 --> 00:06:54.442
By the time he was a teenager, he had

00:06:54.442 --> 00:06:56.582
joined a professional comedy troupe,

00:06:56.992 --> 00:06:59.062
Fred Karno's company, one of the most

00:06:59.062 --> 00:07:01.432
successful music hall acts in Britain.

00:07:02.462 --> 00:07:05.682
Karno specialised in slapstick comedy,

00:07:06.092 --> 00:07:08.332
physical humour with exaggerated

00:07:08.342 --> 00:07:09.952
movements, and comic timing.

00:07:11.102 --> 00:07:13.392
And Chaplin was good.

00:07:14.062 --> 00:07:14.762
Very good.

00:07:16.032 --> 00:07:18.272
In 1910, Karno’s company

00:07:18.502 --> 00:07:20.312
travelled to the United States.

00:07:21.142 --> 00:07:23.602
And for Chaplin, America

00:07:23.802 --> 00:07:26.502
represented something entirely new.

00:07:28.032 --> 00:07:30.772
Unlike Britain, with its rigid class

00:07:30.782 --> 00:07:33.102
system, into which Chaplin was born

00:07:33.112 --> 00:07:35.772
firmly at the very bottom, the United

00:07:35.772 --> 00:07:38.222
States seemed to offer opportunity

00:07:38.412 --> 00:07:40.612
without asking where you came from.

00:07:42.022 --> 00:07:44.012
And during a second tour,

00:07:44.322 --> 00:07:46.532
Chaplin caught the attention of

00:07:46.532 --> 00:07:48.372
a film producer in Hollywood.

00:07:49.232 --> 00:07:52.272
In 1913, he signed a contract with

00:07:52.292 --> 00:07:55.452
Keystone Studios for the very respectable

00:07:55.452 --> 00:07:59.602
wage of $150 a week, and just like

00:07:59.602 --> 00:08:02.562
that, he crossed another invisible line,

00:08:03.082 --> 00:08:06.122
from stage performer to film actor.

00:08:07.311 --> 00:08:10.841
At first, his roles were unremarkable.

00:08:11.401 --> 00:08:13.561
He played generic comic characters,

00:08:13.861 --> 00:08:16.151
often little more than background

00:08:16.151 --> 00:08:18.541
figures in short slapstick films.

00:08:19.535 --> 00:08:22.831
But Chaplin was quick to experiment.

00:08:23.271 --> 00:08:25.881
He adjusted his costume, his

00:08:25.881 --> 00:08:28.061
walk and his facial expressions.

00:08:29.231 --> 00:08:32.821
And then, almost by accident, he created

00:08:32.831 --> 00:08:35.881
the character that would make him famous:

00:08:36.411 --> 00:08:39.431
the Little Tramp, or simply, The Tramp.

00:08:40.771 --> 00:08:43.221
He was told to put on something funny,

00:08:43.601 --> 00:08:46.441
so he borrowed clothes from other actors:

00:08:46.861 --> 00:08:49.911
baggy trousers, a tight jacket, a small

00:08:49.931 --> 00:08:53.361
bowler hat, oversized shoes, and a cane.

00:08:54.251 --> 00:08:56.201
He added a small toothbrush

00:08:56.241 --> 00:08:58.671
moustache and that was it.

00:08:59.901 --> 00:09:02.021
The Little Tramp, as the character

00:09:02.101 --> 00:09:04.211
became known, was an instant hit.

00:09:05.221 --> 00:09:07.961
A small, shabby figure with impeccable

00:09:07.961 --> 00:09:10.291
manners and a kind heart, getting

00:09:10.291 --> 00:09:12.021
into all sorts of trouble but

00:09:12.261 --> 00:09:14.211
always maintaining his dignity.

00:09:15.321 --> 00:09:18.241
And what made The Tramp so special

00:09:18.641 --> 00:09:20.711
was that he transcended language.

00:09:21.641 --> 00:09:24.931
Remember, these were silent films - no

00:09:24.931 --> 00:09:27.921
dialogue, just actions and expressions.

00:09:29.121 --> 00:09:32.001
Chaplin's genius was in his ability

00:09:32.201 --> 00:09:35.061
to communicate emotion, humour,

00:09:35.491 --> 00:09:37.491
and story through nothing but

00:09:37.501 --> 00:09:39.441
movement and facial expressions.

00:09:40.511 --> 00:09:42.651
Audiences loved The Tramp.

00:09:43.211 --> 00:09:45.301
And the studios quickly noticed.

00:09:46.691 --> 00:09:49.361
Chaplin had signed with Keystone for

00:09:49.361 --> 00:09:52.601
$150 a week, which was double what

00:09:52.611 --> 00:09:54.441
he had been earning with Fred Karno.

00:09:55.251 --> 00:09:57.561
Not bad for a young man from the

00:09:57.561 --> 00:09:59.351
workhouses of Victorian London.

00:10:00.011 --> 00:10:01.911
But within just one year,

00:10:02.121 --> 00:10:04.031
his value had exploded.

00:10:05.291 --> 00:10:08.951
In 1915, the Essanay Film Manufacturing

00:10:08.951 --> 00:10:11.461
Company lured him away from Keystone

00:10:11.691 --> 00:10:15.351
with an offer of $1,250 a week,

00:10:15.601 --> 00:10:18.821
plus a $10,000 signing bonus.

00:10:19.821 --> 00:10:23.001
To put that in context, $10,000 in

00:10:23.001 --> 00:10:27.461
1915 would be well over $300,000 today.

00:10:28.171 --> 00:10:29.761
But that was nothing

00:10:29.941 --> 00:10:31.761
compared to what came next.

00:10:33.011 --> 00:10:36.191
In February 1916, just two years

00:10:36.411 --> 00:10:39.031
after making his first film, Chaplin

00:10:39.301 --> 00:10:41.521
signed a contract with the Mutual

00:10:41.531 --> 00:10:43.911
Film Corporation that shocked the

00:10:43.911 --> 00:10:45.661
entire entertainment industry.

00:10:46.351 --> 00:10:49.981
$10,000 per week, plus a

00:10:49.981 --> 00:10:53.111
$150,000 signing bonus.

00:10:54.461 --> 00:10:59.021
In total, $670,000 for one year's work,

00:10:59.371 --> 00:11:02.631
more than $20 million in today’s money.

00:11:04.051 --> 00:11:07.261
At 26 years old, Charlie Chaplin had

00:11:07.261 --> 00:11:09.471
become the highest-paid person in the

00:11:09.471 --> 00:11:12.491
film industry, and arguably one of the

00:11:12.491 --> 00:11:15.141
highest-paid people in the entire world.

00:11:16.151 --> 00:11:18.261
The newspapers couldn't believe it.

00:11:18.641 --> 00:11:21.011
The contract made front-page headlines.

00:11:21.411 --> 00:11:23.871
People were astonished that someone

00:11:23.871 --> 00:11:26.101
could be paid such an astronomical

00:11:26.101 --> 00:11:28.791
sum just to make people laugh.

00:11:29.921 --> 00:11:32.531
But the studio president explained it

00:11:32.611 --> 00:11:35.501
simply: "We can afford to pay Mr. Chaplin

00:11:35.731 --> 00:11:38.031
this large sum annually because the public

00:11:38.031 --> 00:11:39.721
wants Chaplin and will pay for him."

00:11:41.201 --> 00:11:42.661
And they did pay.

00:11:43.251 --> 00:11:45.501
Chaplin's films were hugely

00:11:45.651 --> 00:11:46.891
commercially successful.

00:11:48.001 --> 00:11:50.291
By the early 1920s, Charlie

00:11:50.301 --> 00:11:51.981
Chaplin was one of the most

00:11:51.981 --> 00:11:53.491
famous people on the planet.

00:11:54.221 --> 00:11:56.861
His films were shown everywhere from New

00:11:56.861 --> 00:11:59.981
York to Tokyo, from Paris to Buenos Aires.

00:12:01.221 --> 00:12:03.791
And he wasn't just acting in films.

00:12:04.611 --> 00:12:08.221
In 1919, he co-founded United Artists,

00:12:08.401 --> 00:12:10.681
a film studio, alongside some of the

00:12:10.681 --> 00:12:13.011
biggest stars and directors of the era.

00:12:14.131 --> 00:12:16.251
This gave Chaplin something

00:12:16.411 --> 00:12:19.051
that few actors had: complete

00:12:19.321 --> 00:12:21.541
artistic control over his work.

00:12:22.231 --> 00:12:24.991
He chose the stories, directed the films,

00:12:25.371 --> 00:12:28.401
edited them, and even composed the music.

00:12:28.941 --> 00:12:31.561
He worked slowly, obsessively,

00:12:31.831 --> 00:12:34.291
and entirely on his own terms.

00:12:35.661 --> 00:12:38.591
And he was a legendary perfectionist.

00:12:39.441 --> 00:12:41.411
There are stories of him shooting

00:12:41.411 --> 00:12:46.861
the same scene 50, 100, once even 342

00:12:46.861 --> 00:12:49.411
times, until it was exactly right.

00:12:50.591 --> 00:12:52.181
But, it worked.

00:12:52.691 --> 00:12:53.891
They were masterpieces.

00:12:54.641 --> 00:12:57.471
The Kid, in 1921, mixing

00:12:57.501 --> 00:12:59.741
comedy with genuine pathos.

00:13:00.081 --> 00:13:03.671
The Gold Rush in 1925, with its iconic

00:13:03.681 --> 00:13:06.611
scene of Chaplin eating a boiled shoe.

00:13:07.121 --> 00:13:11.051
City Lights in 1931, a love story that

00:13:11.051 --> 00:13:13.301
made audiences around the world weep.

00:13:14.691 --> 00:13:17.761
But the film industry was changing,

00:13:18.081 --> 00:13:20.001
and was about to have its biggest

00:13:20.011 --> 00:13:23.211
shift to date: by the late 1920s,

00:13:23.581 --> 00:13:25.931
so-called "talkies" had arrived.

00:13:26.291 --> 00:13:28.771
Films with sound, with dialogue.

00:13:29.371 --> 00:13:31.631
The entire industry was transforming.

00:13:32.851 --> 00:13:34.511
Chaplin resisted.

00:13:35.571 --> 00:13:38.571
He believed, probably correctly, that

00:13:38.581 --> 00:13:41.591
The Tramp's universal appeal came from

00:13:41.591 --> 00:13:44.131
his silence, from the fact that he

00:13:44.141 --> 00:13:46.991
could be understood by anyone, anywhere,

00:13:47.271 --> 00:13:49.591
regardless of what language they spoke.

00:13:50.621 --> 00:13:52.731
He continued making silent films

00:13:52.761 --> 00:13:55.491
well into the 1930s, long after

00:13:55.491 --> 00:13:56.911
everyone else had moved on.

00:13:58.321 --> 00:13:59.831
And remarkably, they were

00:13:59.831 --> 00:14:01.431
still hugely successful.

00:14:02.401 --> 00:14:04.991
But as his professional success

00:14:04.991 --> 00:14:07.591
continued, his personal life was

00:14:07.591 --> 00:14:09.421
becoming increasingly complicated,

00:14:09.851 --> 00:14:12.041
and his political views were

00:14:12.041 --> 00:14:13.981
making him powerful enemies.

00:14:15.291 --> 00:14:18.231
Chaplin had a pattern of relationships

00:14:18.351 --> 00:14:21.091
with very young women, relationships

00:14:21.361 --> 00:14:23.621
that would almost certainly be considered

00:14:23.711 --> 00:14:25.701
predatory by today’s standards.

00:14:26.591 --> 00:14:29.061
He married four times, and three

00:14:29.081 --> 00:14:31.141
of his wives were teenagers

00:14:31.321 --> 00:14:32.861
when the relationships began.

00:14:33.801 --> 00:14:35.741
His second wife, Lita Grey,

00:14:36.041 --> 00:14:37.771
was 16 when they married.

00:14:38.301 --> 00:14:40.001
His fourth wife, Oona

00:14:40.001 --> 00:14:43.221
O'Neill, was 18 and he was 54.

00:14:44.318 --> 00:14:45.798
The most damaging episode

00:14:46.008 --> 00:14:48.498
came in the mid-1920s, during

00:14:48.498 --> 00:14:50.068
his marriage to Lita Grey.

00:14:50.968 --> 00:14:53.338
When the marriage collapsed, Grey

00:14:53.518 --> 00:14:56.528
filed for divorce and accused Chaplin

00:14:56.768 --> 00:14:59.168
of cruelty and what she described

00:14:59.358 --> 00:15:01.968
as “perverted sexual desires”.

00:15:03.448 --> 00:15:05.408
The case never went to trial.

00:15:05.748 --> 00:15:08.388
Chaplin settled out of court, paying

00:15:08.388 --> 00:15:11.108
a very large sum of money, and all

00:15:11.138 --> 00:15:13.538
the details were never legally tested.

00:15:14.158 --> 00:15:17.008
But the accusations were widely

00:15:17.008 --> 00:15:19.768
reported in the press, and for the

00:15:19.768 --> 00:15:22.428
first time, Chaplin’s image as a

00:15:22.428 --> 00:15:25.418
lovable underdog was seriously damaged.

00:15:26.228 --> 00:15:28.114
It was a turning point.

00:15:29.048 --> 00:15:31.508
From this moment on, Chaplin

00:15:31.798 --> 00:15:33.638
was no longer just a comedian.

00:15:34.028 --> 00:15:35.858
He was a controversial public

00:15:35.858 --> 00:15:38.768
figure, watched closely, criticised

00:15:38.788 --> 00:15:41.748
harshly, and judged not only for

00:15:41.748 --> 00:15:44.238
his work, but for his character.

00:15:45.098 --> 00:15:47.318
In the 1930s, as the world

00:15:47.508 --> 00:15:49.408
changed rapidly, Chaplin’s

00:15:49.408 --> 00:15:51.348
films began to change too.

00:15:52.188 --> 00:15:53.548
He had been resisting the move

00:15:53.548 --> 00:15:55.638
to sound films longer than most,

00:15:55.918 --> 00:15:58.318
worried that dialogue would destroy

00:15:58.318 --> 00:16:00.548
the universality of his work.

00:16:01.538 --> 00:16:03.178
But when he did speak,

00:16:03.408 --> 00:16:04.728
he did so deliberately.

00:16:05.668 --> 00:16:09.008
In Modern Times, in 1936, he

00:16:09.008 --> 00:16:11.038
criticised the dehumanising

00:16:11.038 --> 00:16:13.178
effects of industrial capitalism.

00:16:13.868 --> 00:16:17.988
And in 1940, he took an even bigger risk.

00:16:19.178 --> 00:16:21.558
He took a jab at someone whose

00:16:21.558 --> 00:16:23.758
life and his were curiously

00:16:23.768 --> 00:16:26.168
intertwined: Adolf Hitler.

00:16:27.638 --> 00:16:29.968
The two men were born just four

00:16:29.968 --> 00:16:33.048
days apart, in April of 1889.

00:16:34.168 --> 00:16:36.218
They had both escaped poverty

00:16:36.448 --> 00:16:38.578
through charisma and performance,

00:16:38.928 --> 00:16:41.038
albeit in very different ways.

00:16:42.438 --> 00:16:44.698
They were both instantly recognisable.

00:16:46.008 --> 00:16:47.568
And they had the same

00:16:47.768 --> 00:16:49.298
little dark moustache.

00:16:50.431 --> 00:16:52.828
Chaplin’s response was The Great

00:16:52.878 --> 00:16:56.118
Dictator, which was released in 1940.

00:16:56.948 --> 00:16:59.518
It was his first true sound film,

00:16:59.848 --> 00:17:02.548
and it was a bold, risky move.

00:17:04.038 --> 00:17:06.368
At the time, the United States had

00:17:06.368 --> 00:17:07.728
not yet entered the Second World

00:17:07.728 --> 00:17:10.408
War, and many in Hollywood were

00:17:10.408 --> 00:17:13.378
reluctant to criticise Hitler openly.

00:17:14.298 --> 00:17:15.738
Chaplin was not.

00:17:16.848 --> 00:17:19.458
In the film, he plays two roles:

00:17:19.838 --> 00:17:22.238
a brutal dictator, clearly based

00:17:22.238 --> 00:17:24.938
on Hitler, and a humble Jewish

00:17:24.958 --> 00:17:27.318
barber who looks exactly like him.

00:17:28.138 --> 00:17:30.568
Through satire and exaggeration,

00:17:30.928 --> 00:17:33.948
Chaplin mocked fascism, militarism,

00:17:34.158 --> 00:17:36.278
and the cult of personality that

00:17:36.278 --> 00:17:38.108
surrounded authoritarian leaders.

00:17:39.198 --> 00:17:41.188
And then, at the end of the film,

00:17:41.518 --> 00:17:43.288
something remarkable happens.

00:17:44.118 --> 00:17:45.398
The comedy stops.

00:17:46.288 --> 00:17:48.958
Chaplin steps forward and delivers

00:17:48.978 --> 00:17:52.138
a long, emotional speech, not as the

00:17:52.158 --> 00:17:55.838
Tramp, not as a clown, but as himself.

00:17:56.538 --> 00:17:58.478
He speaks about humanity,

00:17:58.838 --> 00:18:01.298
kindness, democracy, and the

00:18:01.298 --> 00:18:03.798
dangers of hatred and division.

00:18:04.818 --> 00:18:07.388
It is a deeply sincere moment,

00:18:07.678 --> 00:18:10.048
and it shocked audiences who were

00:18:10.048 --> 00:18:12.208
used to seeing Chaplin communicate

00:18:12.468 --> 00:18:15.008
only through gestures and silence.

00:18:16.408 --> 00:18:17.928
Some people loved it.

00:18:18.398 --> 00:18:20.508
Others were deeply uncomfortable.

00:18:21.288 --> 00:18:23.378
To some, Chaplin was a

00:18:23.408 --> 00:18:25.098
courageous moral voice.

00:18:25.748 --> 00:18:27.598
To others, he was a foreigner

00:18:27.828 --> 00:18:30.018
lecturing America about politics.

00:18:31.068 --> 00:18:33.728
And this is where Chaplin’s problems

00:18:33.898 --> 00:18:35.988
with the United States really began.

00:18:37.298 --> 00:18:40.338
During the 1940s, America entered a

00:18:40.378 --> 00:18:43.138
period of intense political paranoia.

00:18:43.758 --> 00:18:46.678
Fear of communism spread through politics,

00:18:46.918 --> 00:18:49.318
the media, and the entertainment industry.

00:18:50.018 --> 00:18:52.588
Anyone with left-wing sympathies,

00:18:52.898 --> 00:18:54.928
or even vaguely progressive

00:18:54.938 --> 00:18:57.138
views, could fall under suspicion.

00:18:58.258 --> 00:19:00.308
Chaplin had never been a member

00:19:00.318 --> 00:19:02.658
of the Communist Party, but he

00:19:02.658 --> 00:19:04.508
was openly critical of capitalism,

00:19:04.878 --> 00:19:06.868
supportive of workers’ rights,

00:19:07.078 --> 00:19:09.568
and vocal about social inequality.

00:19:10.658 --> 00:19:12.748
He had also never become an

00:19:12.748 --> 00:19:15.258
American citizen, despite having

00:19:15.258 --> 00:19:17.138
lived in the country for decades.

00:19:18.518 --> 00:19:20.948
To figures like J. Edgar Hoover,

00:19:21.078 --> 00:19:23.138
the powerful head of the FBI,

00:19:23.818 --> 00:19:25.728
Chaplin looked suspicious.

00:19:27.128 --> 00:19:29.458
The FBI opened a file on him.

00:19:29.918 --> 00:19:31.288
His speeches were analysed.

00:19:31.508 --> 00:19:33.918
His personal life was scrutinised.

00:19:34.178 --> 00:19:37.438
His past scandals were quietly revisited.

00:19:38.258 --> 00:19:41.138
And newspapers began to portray him

00:19:41.478 --> 00:19:43.988
not just as morally questionable,

00:19:44.238 --> 00:19:46.458
but as politically dangerous.

00:19:47.473 --> 00:19:49.513
Then came another scandal

00:19:50.313 --> 00:19:52.473
In the early 1940s, a young

00:19:52.473 --> 00:19:55.273
woman called Joan Barry accused

00:19:55.273 --> 00:19:57.623
Chaplin of fathering her child.

00:19:58.633 --> 00:20:01.243
Blood tests showed that he was not

00:20:01.263 --> 00:20:04.013
the father, but under California law

00:20:04.043 --> 00:20:06.423
at the time, this did not matter.

00:20:06.933 --> 00:20:08.623
Chaplin was still ordered

00:20:08.813 --> 00:20:10.053
to pay child support.

00:20:10.813 --> 00:20:12.953
Once again, the legal outcome

00:20:13.123 --> 00:20:14.923
mattered less than the headlines.

00:20:16.393 --> 00:20:19.793
By the early 1950s, Chaplin had become

00:20:19.793 --> 00:20:22.363
a deeply divisive figure in America.

00:20:23.103 --> 00:20:24.623
He was admired by many,

00:20:24.843 --> 00:20:26.403
but hated by others.

00:20:27.333 --> 00:20:30.193
Protesters gathered outside his films.

00:20:30.473 --> 00:20:32.963
Politicians spoke openly about

00:20:32.963 --> 00:20:34.693
removing him from the country.

00:20:35.643 --> 00:20:38.853
And in 1952, while Chaplin was

00:20:38.853 --> 00:20:40.403
travelling to Europe for the

00:20:40.403 --> 00:20:42.513
premiere of a new film, the US

00:20:42.543 --> 00:20:45.423
government revoked his re-entry visa.

00:20:46.303 --> 00:20:47.743
There was no trial.

00:20:47.833 --> 00:20:49.613
No dramatic expulsion.

00:20:50.023 --> 00:20:52.013
Just a bureaucratic decision.

00:20:53.553 --> 00:20:55.633
Chaplin realised that

00:20:55.633 --> 00:20:56.813
he was not welcome back.

00:20:58.073 --> 00:21:01.263
At the age of 63, after spending

00:21:01.433 --> 00:21:03.563
almost forty years in the United

00:21:03.563 --> 00:21:05.593
States, his adopted country,

00:21:06.083 --> 00:21:08.733
Charlie Chaplin went into exile.

00:21:10.173 --> 00:21:12.643
He settled in Switzerland, in a quiet

00:21:12.643 --> 00:21:15.083
village overlooking Lake Geneva, with

00:21:15.083 --> 00:21:16.903
his wife Oona and their children.

00:21:18.243 --> 00:21:20.953
He continued to work, but he was no

00:21:20.953 --> 00:21:23.483
longer at the centre of global culture.

00:21:24.463 --> 00:21:26.123
The man who had once been the

00:21:26.123 --> 00:21:28.593
most famous person on Earth now

00:21:28.593 --> 00:21:30.893
lived a relatively private life,

00:21:31.303 --> 00:21:33.363
making a few films, but nothing

00:21:33.363 --> 00:21:35.593
compared to his previous successes.

00:21:37.063 --> 00:21:39.103
For years, he refused to

00:21:39.103 --> 00:21:41.003
return to the United States.

00:21:42.293 --> 00:21:43.563
Gradually, however,

00:21:44.073 --> 00:21:46.103
attitudes began to change.

00:21:46.633 --> 00:21:49.460
The hysteria of the Red Scare faded.

00:21:50.176 --> 00:21:52.653
Chaplin’s films were re-evaluated.

00:21:53.173 --> 00:21:55.023
A new generation discovered

00:21:55.023 --> 00:21:57.213
his work, not as political

00:21:57.213 --> 00:22:00.123
provocation, but as timeless art.

00:22:01.713 --> 00:22:04.333
And in 1972, something

00:22:04.343 --> 00:22:05.593
extraordinary happened.

00:22:06.733 --> 00:22:08.633
The Academy of Motion Picture Arts

00:22:08.633 --> 00:22:11.163
and Sciences, the organisation behind

00:22:11.163 --> 00:22:14.393
the Oscars, invited Chaplin back to

00:22:14.393 --> 00:22:16.553
Los Angeles to receive an honourary

00:22:16.573 --> 00:22:18.933
award for his contribution to cinema.

00:22:20.453 --> 00:22:21.443
He accepted.

00:22:22.233 --> 00:22:27.153
On April 10th, 1972, a frail 83-year-old

00:22:27.193 --> 00:22:29.543
Charlie Chaplin walked onto the stage

00:22:29.683 --> 00:22:31.553
at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.

00:22:32.243 --> 00:22:34.583
The audience rose to their feet.

00:22:35.593 --> 00:22:37.373
And they kept clapping.

00:22:37.803 --> 00:22:38.503
And clapping.

00:22:39.043 --> 00:22:39.773
And clapping.

00:22:40.783 --> 00:22:44.223
The standing ovation lasted twelve minutes

00:22:44.243 --> 00:22:46.763
- one of the longest in Oscar history.

00:22:47.823 --> 00:22:50.173
Chaplin, visibly moved,

00:22:50.583 --> 00:22:51.633
struggled to speak.

00:22:52.703 --> 00:22:54.563
When he finally could, he simply

00:22:54.563 --> 00:22:58.433
said: "Words seem so futile, so

00:22:58.633 --> 00:23:01.213
feeble... Thank you so very much."

00:23:03.063 --> 00:23:04.803
Three years later, Queen

00:23:04.813 --> 00:23:06.793
Elizabeth II knighted him.

00:23:07.233 --> 00:23:09.253
He became Sir Charles Chaplin.

00:23:10.313 --> 00:23:13.063
And two years after that, on Christmas

00:23:13.063 --> 00:23:16.333
Day, 1977, at his lakeside home in

00:23:16.333 --> 00:23:19.713
Switzerland, he died at the age of 88.

00:23:21.163 --> 00:23:23.423
So, what should we make

00:23:23.493 --> 00:23:24.353
of Charlie Chaplin?

00:23:25.373 --> 00:23:27.453
Here was a man who created the most

00:23:27.463 --> 00:23:29.893
universal character in the history of

00:23:29.893 --> 00:23:33.193
cinema - a character who spoke no words

00:23:33.383 --> 00:23:36.033
yet was understood in every language.

00:23:36.613 --> 00:23:38.883
A character who represented the

00:23:38.883 --> 00:23:40.953
little guy, the underdog, the

00:23:40.953 --> 00:23:42.913
person trying to maintain their

00:23:42.913 --> 00:23:45.453
dignity in an undignified world.

00:23:46.273 --> 00:23:48.133
What might have seemed controversial

00:23:48.133 --> 00:23:50.453
at the time, speaking out against

00:23:50.653 --> 00:23:53.103
Adolf Hitler, was undoubtedly an

00:23:53.123 --> 00:23:55.243
admirable and correct thing to do.

00:23:56.563 --> 00:23:59.833
And yet the man himself was deeply flawed.

00:24:00.883 --> 00:24:02.563
His relationships with young

00:24:02.563 --> 00:24:05.233
women were, by today's standards

00:24:05.273 --> 00:24:06.613
and even by the standards of his

00:24:06.613 --> 00:24:08.753
own time, deeply inappropriate.

00:24:09.523 --> 00:24:12.313
His political views, whether genuinely

00:24:12.313 --> 00:24:14.873
held or simply naively expressed,

00:24:15.183 --> 00:24:17.633
made him enemies in powerful places.

00:24:18.883 --> 00:24:21.433
But perhaps that's what makes

00:24:21.433 --> 00:24:22.853
his story so fascinating.

00:24:23.573 --> 00:24:24.663
He wasn't a saint.

00:24:25.043 --> 00:24:26.573
He was complicated,

00:24:27.063 --> 00:24:29.583
contradictory, and controversial.

00:24:30.383 --> 00:24:32.693
A man who brought joy to hundreds

00:24:32.693 --> 00:24:35.573
of millions on screen, while in his

00:24:35.603 --> 00:24:38.053
personal life he was clearly capable

00:24:38.163 --> 00:24:40.033
of causing a great amount of pain

00:24:40.303 --> 00:24:41.943
to people he should have loved.

00:24:42.813 --> 00:24:44.963
From the workhouses of Victorian

00:24:44.963 --> 00:24:46.993
London to the stages of Hollywood.

00:24:47.213 --> 00:24:49.863
From beloved icon to exiled pariah

00:24:50.283 --> 00:24:52.063
and back to honoured legend.

00:24:52.913 --> 00:24:55.013
A fitting ending, perhaps, for

00:24:55.023 --> 00:24:57.663
a man once described as “the

00:24:57.663 --> 00:25:00.353
greatest clown ever to have lived”.

00:25:01.983 --> 00:25:04.083
OK, then, that is it for today's

00:25:04.093 --> 00:25:05.943
episode on Charlie Chaplin.

00:25:06.233 --> 00:25:07.543
I hope it's been an interesting one

00:25:07.783 --> 00:25:09.483
and that you've learnt something new.

00:25:10.133 --> 00:25:11.643
As always, I would love to know

00:25:11.643 --> 00:25:13.043
what you thought of this episode.

00:25:13.413 --> 00:25:14.533
Did you know this about

00:25:14.533 --> 00:25:15.693
Charlie Chaplin’s life?

00:25:16.033 --> 00:25:17.983
Are his films popular in your country?

00:25:18.263 --> 00:25:20.533
And what other actors or actresses

00:25:20.683 --> 00:25:22.173
would you like to hear about next?

00:25:22.543 --> 00:25:24.083
I would love to know, so let’s

00:25:24.083 --> 00:25:25.393
get this discussion started.

00:25:25.693 --> 00:25:26.693
You can head right into our

00:25:26.693 --> 00:25:28.323
community forum, which is at

00:25:28.323 --> 00:25:30.983
community.leonardoenglish.com and get

00:25:30.983 --> 00:25:33.203
chatting away to other curious minds.

00:25:33.893 --> 00:25:35.673
You've been listening to English Learning

00:25:35.673 --> 00:25:38.373
for Curious Minds by Leonardo English.

00:25:38.743 --> 00:25:41.413
I'm Alastair Budge, you stay safe, and

00:25:41.413 --> 00:25:43.753
I'll catch you in the next episode.

